The quick and hacky way that I do this is with print/println, adding a "depth" argument to the recursive function. Whenever it calls itself, I add 1 to the depth argument. Then, I make it print out its arguments first thing with a number of "=" signs in front.<br /><br />Something like:<br /><br /><pre><code>def rec = (arg0) =&gt;
  def recInner = (arg0, depth) =&gt;
    println("%s&gt; %d".format("=" * depth, arg0))
    ...
    return recInner(arg, depth+1) + recInner(arg, depth+1)
  return recInner(arg0, 0)</code></pre><br />This gets you output that's indented according to the recursion depth.

