Perhaps an example helps...<br /><br /><pre><code>// The set integers 1 to 10
val oneToTen: Set = i =&gt; i &gt; 0 &amp;&amp; i &lt;= 10

// Are there any multiples of 3 in the set ?
// Create a predicate which tests whether a value is a multiple of 3
// and use 'exists' to test:
val p = (i: Int) =&gt; i % 3 == 0
exists(oneToTen, p)

// Same thing more concisely
exists(oneToTen, i =&gt; i % 3 == 0)

// You can even chain predicates together.
// For example, are there two different values (let's call them i and j)
// in the set which sum to 19 ?
exists(oneToTen, i =&gt; exists(oneToTen, j =&gt; i != j &amp;&amp; i + j == 19))</code></pre>As Federico says, both Set and Predicate are actually the same under the hood: a function which takes an Int and returns a Boolean. But treating them as separate things in terms of their usage makes for easier reasoning and more readable code.

Copying below the invert function based on Professor's Newton's approximation code example. It does not work for all cases but works for your example. As the name implies, invert function <i>attempts </i>to return the invert of `f` i.e. if f(x) is y then invert(f)(y) is <i>hopefully </i>x.<br /><br />EDIT: Sending improved guess to next iteration. The guesses were not correct in last version.<br /><br /><pre>def invert(f: Int =&gt; Int)(x: Int): Int = {

  // gets the slope of function f at a point px
  def slope(y: Int): Int = {
    (f(y + 1) - f(y - 1)) / 2 // (y2 - y1) / (x2 - x1)
  }

  // guesses next best point using
  def iterate(guess: Int): Int = {
    if (f(guess) == x) guess
    iterate(guess + (x - f(guess)) / slope(guess))
  }

  iterate(0)
}</pre><br />The unbounded map function will return a set, that will evaluate to true for integer x if and only if its parent set evaluates to true for integer invert(f)(x)<br /><br /><pre>def map(s: Set, trans: Int =&gt; Int): Set = (x: Int) =&gt; s(invert(trans)(x))</pre><br /><b>DISCLAIMER<br /><br /></b>It only works for a limited set of functions like addition, subtraction, and multiplication (with several exceptions). The functions should be strictly increasing/decreasing. I am only trying to provide a possible resolution to Martin's question. We cannot use it for:<br /><br />- Integer division, since f(x) does not strictly increase. 0/4 and 1/4 are same<br /><strong></strong>- Square, since f(x) since again, f(x) does not increase or decrease for entire range of x.<br />- Hash function or constant function. Same reason.<br /><br />There are more exceptions resulting due to integer arithmetic.<br /><br /><pre>val s1 = singletonSet(10000)

val s2 = map(s1, _ + 1)
println(s2(10000)) // false
println(s2(10001)) // true

val s3 = map(s1, _ * 2)
println(s3(19998)) // false, input should be multiple of two to evaluate to 9999
println(s3(20000)) // true<br /></pre>

