I think it might help you to avoid anonymous functions until you are comfortable with them, since they are actually just "syntactic sugar". When I learned functional programming I found it to be very helpful to spell things out explicitly (for years).<br /><br />So for exists, we can name a useful function:<br /><br /><pre><code>def exists(s: Set, p: Int =&gt; Boolean): Boolean = {
  def notP(x: Int): Boolean = !p(x) // I just defined a new function which is true when p(x) fails
  !forall(s, notP) // an element of s satisfies p if not all elements fail p
}</code></pre><br />map() is a bit harder, and to be honest it expresses a fairly deep concept for this stage in the course.<br /><br />I think the best way to start is to remember that a Set is actually a function from Ints to Booleans. That is, a Set is a thing which can say whether or not a given Int is in it. map(s, f) returns a Set, so it needs to be able to say "true" or "false" when asked whether some Int "y" is in it.<br /><br />Per the instructions, the set map(s, f) is a new set containing any Int that is the result of calling f() on an Int that is  in s. In other words, if an Int y is in map(s, f), then s must contain some Int (call it x) such that f(x) = y. We can express this in terms of exists, with no anonymous functions:<br /><br /><pre><code>def map(s: Set, f: Int =&gt; Int): Set = {
  def someXinSMapsToY(y: Int): Boolean = {
    def thisXMapsToY(x: Int): Boolean = 
      f(x) == y
    exists(s, thisXMapsToY)
  }
  someXinSMapsToY
}</code></pre><br />This is a bit complicated, but we can see what's happening piecewise. I think it's easiest to start in the middle. thisXMapsToY(x) is true whenever f(x) == y, which is straightforward. We use it as the test in exists() to find out whether or not any element of s maps to y. The final return value is this function (someXinSMapsToY) which returns "true" when called on "y" that passes this exists() test.<br /><br />In case it is helpful to see the anonymous version of map:<br /><br /><pre><code>def map2(s: Set, f: Int =&gt; Int): Set = 
    (y: Int) =&gt; exists(s, (x: Int) =&gt; f(x) == y)<br /></code></pre>"(x: Int) =&gt; f(x) == y" is equivalent to thisXMapsToY, and the entire second line is equivalent to someXinSMapsToY.<br /><br />I hope I haven't made things worse.<br /><br />

