Hi Dmitri,<br /><br />good question. The thing is, pattern matching in Scala is fully customizable. When you write<br /><pre><code>x match {
  case Foo(y) =&gt; doStuff()
}</code></pre>it gets desugared into a call to the special unapply method of the Foo object. Without getting into details, it will be something like this:<br /><pre><code>Foo.unapply(x)</code></pre>This unapply method you can define anyway you want. The case class modifier just adds a default unapply method in the respective companion object, that returns the arguments you passed into the case class constructor. <br /><br />So the compiler cannot insert the case modifier for you, because that would constrain the flexibility of pattern matching.<br />

Hi,<br />nice question, this is good high- level thinking. The solution is to utilize that pattern matching is customizable in Scala. So what you can do is define your "flat" class hierarchy (just Expr and case classes inheriting directly from it) and then add additional, customized "pattern-matchers" to do what you want. The way to do it is to define the unapply method in the respecive object. E.g.<br /><br /><pre><code>object AddSub {
  def unapply(e : Expr) : Option[Expr] = e match {
    case s : Sub =&gt; Some(s)
    case a : Add =&gt; Some(a)
    case _ =&gt; None
  }
}</code></pre>The idea is that the unapply function returns a Some in the cases you want the pattern matching to succeed, and the content of this some is the subpatterns you retrieve from the pattern matching. If pattern matching should fail, you return None. So now you can write<br /><br /><pre><code>this match {
  case Prod(AddSub(l), AddSub(r)) =&gt; s"($l)*($r)"
  ...
}</code></pre><br />(btw, this is called string interpolation and you should use it instead of String.format in Scala).<br /><br />This is quite advanced Scala material, but I hope it will motivate you to look further into it! <br /><br />

